{"author":{"id":"cdea3c8cb23f0b3da966d6f7435a55d55c0ff2450c9ecdcad89555037aac8fec"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1564580403,"nonce":"l7Tj9SiOafiP8nF0/rvE+zvciUk=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU0NzUxNTE1OTE=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/2513","origin":"github"},"title":"README.rst for Trinity gives incorrect instructions for setting memory limit","message":"The `README.rst` file for the `trinity` tool (https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/tree/master/tools/trinity) has incorrect instructions for setting the memory consumption limit.\n\nThe instructions indicate that values of the form `1G`, `50G` etc (i.e. a number followed by `G`) can be assigned to the `GALAXY_MEMORY_MB` environment limits, but doing this results in the following message appearing in the tool stdout:\n\n    .../job_scripts/597189: line 53: 50G: value too great for base (error token is \"50G\")\n\nand the default value of `1G` is supplied to `trinity` on the command line.\n\nIt appears that the memory limit actually needs to be assigned as a number of MB without the units, e.g. for 50G limit this would be (50*1024 =) 51200:\n\n    \u003cenv id=\"GALAXY_MEMORY_MB\"\u003e51200\u003c/env\u003e","files":null}]}